	abstract = {Trees are a crucial component of urban environments. However, accurately identifying and segmenting individual street trees from Mobile Laser Scanning (MLS) point clouds in complex urban scenes remains a significant challenge due to low accuracy and poor robustness. Additionally, traditional manual extraction methods are labor-intensive and time-consuming. To address these issues, this paper proposes a method for the automatic extraction and segmentation of urban street trees using MLS point cloud data. The preprocessing phase initially filters out ground and building points to reduce computational complexity. Subsequently, coarse extraction is performed using projection density, and a method based on spatial morphology and elevation slice frequency statistics is employed to differentiate other objects and cluster street trees. Next, the Principal Component Analysis (PCA) algorithm is employed to initialize the potential tree trunk point cloud, and precise identification of tree trunks is achieved through the application of circular arc curvature and a layered circular fitting model. Finally, a combination of neighborhood-based connectivity coefficients and a shortest path constraint method is utilized to accurately segment multiple overlapping street trees. Evaluation results from multiple sets of experimental datasets indicate that the proposed algorithm achieves a high level of accuracy in trunk extraction, resulting in clearer outlines of the segmented tree crowns. The detection accuracy and precision of individual tree clusters are approximately 95.3\% and 96.7\%, respectively, presenting more robust segmentation results compared to mainstream methods. This contributes significantly to providing crucial technical references for urban tree census and statistics.},
